# **6. Why does this work?**

The **Min Stack** always stores the minimum value corresponding to every position in the main stack.

Whenever we push a new element:

* If it is smaller than the current minimum, it becomes the new minimum.
* Otherwise, we store the current minimum again.

Whenever we pop:

* Both stacks remove one element.
* The previous minimum is automatically restored.

Thus, `getMin()` simply returns the top of the Min Stack in **O(1)** time.

---

# **7. Java Code**

```java
class MinStack {

    Stack<Integer> stack;
    Stack<Integer> minStack;

    public MinStack() {
        stack = new Stack<>();
        minStack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public void push(int val) {

        stack.push(val);

        if (minStack.isEmpty()) {
            minStack.push(val);
        } else {
            minStack.push(Math.min(val, minStack.peek()));
        }
    }

    public void pop() {
        stack.pop();
        minStack.pop();
    }

    public int top() {
        return stack.peek();
    }

    public int getMin() {
        return minStack.peek();
    }
}
```

---

# **8. Time Complexity**

| Operation | Time Complexity |
| --------- | --------------- |
| push()    | **O(1)**        |
| pop()     | **O(1)**        |
| top()     | **O(1)**        |
| getMin()  | **O(1)**        |

---

# **9. Space Complexity**

**O(n)**

* `n` = number of elements in the stack.
* We use two stacks, each storing `n` elements.

---

# **10. Important Interview Note**

The trick is **not** to search for the minimum every time.

Instead, **store the minimum so far** along with every push operation.

The Min Stack mirrors the Main Stack:

* Every push → push into both stacks.
* Every pop → pop from both stacks.
* `getMin()` becomes a simple `peek()` operation.

This is a classic interview question that demonstrates how to trade **extra space** for **constant-time queries**.

---

# **11. One-line Note for Interviews**

**Use two stacks—one for all elements and another for the minimum value at each level. The top of the Min Stack always gives the current minimum in O(1) time.** 🚀
